ETSI ES 202 336-2 — Environmental Engineering (EE); Monitoring and control interface for DC power systems used in telecommunication cell sites and central offices (excerpt). Publisher: ETSI. Applies to -48 V DC plants at macro and small-cell sites monitored from the NOC.

## 1 Scope and monitoring model

This part defines the monitoring model a DC power plant exposes to a Network Operations Centre (NOC): the set of monitored quantities (bus voltage, rectifier module status, battery-string current and temperature, distribution status) and the sensing channel through which each is read. Every monitored quantity at a cell site reaches the supervision/controller unit through one sensing channel: a voltage-sense lead and an analog-to-digital converter for the DC bus, a shunt for string current, a status contact for each rectifier module. In normal operation the reported value equals the monitored quantity, and the monitoring model treats telemetry as truthful by default: an alarm reflects a real plant condition unless a direct measurement shows otherwise. The model separates the plant (the physical -48 V system) from the measurement point (the sensing channel plus the controller input that reports it) so that, in the specific case where they disagree, the disagreement can be attributed correctly.

## 2 Measurement point failure modes — when the sensor, not the plant, fails

A measurement point is itself a component that can fail, but this failure mode must not be inferred from telemetry alone. It is diagnosable only after an independent field measurement contradicts the alarm — the diagnostic precondition is a bus voltage measured at the distribution bar with a calibrated DMM that sits in the normal float envelope while the controller still reports undervoltage. Absent that contradicting measurement, a reported low bus voltage is read as a real plant condition (a rectifier fault and discharge), not a sensor artifact. When, and only when, the field measurement contradicts the reported value, consider these measurement-point failure modes on a -48 V plant: (a) a faulty or drifting supervision/sensing card whose ADC or reference no longer matches the true bus; (b) a corroded, loose or high-resistance voltage-sense connection that reads low; (c) a controller input or calibration fault after a firmware or configuration change. Because bus voltage is read through a single sensing path, that path is a single point of failure for monitoring — so the model's principle that the measurement point, not the plant, can fail is a conclusion reached from the contradicting field measurement, never from the alarm by itself.

## 3 Distinguishing a real plant anomaly from a sensing fault

The arbiter is an independent field measurement, and the default reading before that measurement is that the plant condition is real. When the controller reports a DC undervoltage, a technician measures the bus directly at the distribution bar with a calibrated DMM. If the DMM confirms a low bus (for example around -44.8 V) — especially alongside a rectifier module fault and battery-discharge current — the telemetry is internally coherent and the undervoltage is REAL: a genuine plant fault, acted on as such. Only the opposite outcome indicates a sensing fault: the field measurement reads normal float (for example -53.9 V, well inside the -40.5 to -57.0 V envelope) while the controller still reports undervoltage. A normal bus voltage measured at the bar concurrent with an active undervoltage alarm — the field measurement contradicting the telemetry — is the signature of a measurement-point (sensing/supervision) fault. Supporting a sensing fault only after that contradiction: no thermal ramp, no battery-discharge current, mains present. Without a contradicting field measurement, coherent low-voltage telemetry points to a real plant fault, not the sensor.

## 4 Monitoring point verification and recalibration

To confirm a suspected sensing fault once a field measurement has contradicted the alarm: compare the controller's reported bus voltage against the calibrated DMM reading taken at the same point; if they disagree beyond the channel tolerance, the measurement point is at fault. Recalibrate the voltage-sense input if the controller supports it, or replace the supervision/sensing module. After the sense channel is restored, verify that the controller's reported bus voltage again tracks the DMM within tolerance before the monitoring point is trusted for alarming. Only a verified measurement point should be allowed to drive dispatch decisions.

## 5 Consequence for site health and dispatch priority

Once a field measurement has shown the bus at normal float while the alarm is active, the false undervoltage is confirmed to originate in a sensing card and does not endanger the plant: the true bus voltage and the N+1 rectifier redundancy govern actual health, not the mis-reading channel. In that confirmed-sensing case an emergency battery-reserve intervention is not warranted, and a real-but-non-urgent equipment fault (for example a single failed rectifier module while N+1 redundancy holds) can be demoted to scheduled maintenance. The monitoring visibility is impaired, not the power. This demotion applies only after the contradicting measurement; until then the coherent telemetry is treated as a real plant fault.
